# clustr — Gap analysis vs. clustervisor & detailed improvement plan

> Source data: a side-by-side review of the `clustr` source tree and the
> three RPM packages that constitute clustervisor on this host
> (`clustervisor`, `clustervisor-client`, `clustervisor-server`, version
> `1.25.04-4844`). The clustervisor inventory is reconstructed from
> `rpm -ql` plus inspection of the on-disk Python/Perl modules.
>
> Pair this document with [`OVERVIEW.md`](./OVERVIEW.md) for clustr
> architecture and `PACKAGING.md` (root) for the release pipeline.

---

## TL;DR

clustr is a **modern, narrowly scoped provisioning + portal product**:
single-binary Go server, embedded React UI, signed RPM repos, and a
first-class PI / Director portal that clustervisor never grew. clustervisor
is an **older, broader, plugin-based cluster management toolkit**: it does
provisioning *and* monitoring, *and* operator parallel-exec, *and* SNMP, *and*
sensors, *and* serial consoles, *and* it ships its own Python venv with
pyarmor-encoded license-protected modules.

To displace clustervisor in the field, clustr needs to grow into the operator
parallel-exec, monitoring, and console workflows that an HPC sysadmin uses
every day. The three biggest functional gaps, in priority order:

1. **Day-2 ops surface** — `clustr exec`, `clustr cp`, `clustr console`,
   `clustr sel`, `clustr sensor` (the cv-exec / cv-cp / cv-console / cv-sel /
   cv-sensor equivalents). Without these, sysadmins keep `pdsh` and `ipmitool`
   in their muscle memory and clustr is "just provisioning."
2. **Stats + alerts** — `cv-stats`, `cv-health`, `cv-alerts` plus the plugin
   library (CPU, memory, NICs, IB, GPUs, NVMe, ZFS, MD, megaraid, NFS,
   chronyd, NVIDIA, ROCm, IPMI). Right now clustr exposes Prometheus
   `/metrics` but ships no agent-side collectors and no alerting.
3. **Stateless / diskless image support** (`cv-diskless`, stateless_node,
   stateless_server). clustr is image-based stateful only; many HPC sites
   prefer stateless compute nodes that PXE-boot the image into RAM.

The remainder of this document works through the gaps in detail with
prioritised recommendations.

