## Priority recommendations

The recommendations below are ordered by impact on **operator daily-driver
viability** — i.e. how soon a clustervisor user would be able to retire
clustervisor and use only clustr.

### P0 — Operator parallel ops (`exec`, `cp`, `console`)

**Why P0**: Without these three, an operator who switches from clustervisor
to clustr immediately reaches for `pdsh`, `pdcp`, and `ipmitool sol activate`
the moment the cluster is online. That gap defines the perceived ceiling of
the product.

**Concrete shape**:

```
clustr exec  -g compute "uptime"
clustr exec  -n node[01-32] --format consolidate "rpm -q kernel"
clustr cp -r ./conf/ -n login01,login02:/etc/myapp/
clustr console -n node03                   # IPMI SOL by default
clustr console -n node03 --ssh
```

**Where to add it in the codebase**:

- New CLI subcommands in `cmd/clustr/`. Model the selectors after cv-exec /
  cv-cp: `-n NODE`, `-g GROUP`, `--racks RACK`, `--chassis CHASSIS`, `-A`
  (all), `-a` (active), `--ignore-status`.
- New API endpoints under `/api/v1/exec`, `/api/v1/cp`, `/api/v1/console/{id}`
  in `internal/server/handlers/`. The exec/cp endpoints should be SSE-streamed
  with one stream per target node so operators can use `--format realtime` /
  `--format consolidate` / `--format json`.
- Reuse the existing `clientd` WebSocket as the transport. clustr-clientd
  already runs on every managed node, has a privileged channel to the
  server, and is auth-pinned via a node-scoped API key. The operator's
  command goes server-side → clientd → exec, output streams back. No new
  SSH / port management needed on the operator workstation.
- For console: stream raw IPMI SOL bytes (or SSH PTY bytes) to the CLI over
  a WebSocket, terminating with the same escape character convention
  (`-e CHAR`, default `~.`). The shell-manager pattern at
  `internal/image/shell.go` is the reference implementation; generalise it.
- Output formats: implement `inline`, `header`, `consolidate`, `realtime`,
  `json` to match cv-exec exactly. Operators' shell scripts will copy-paste.

**Time estimate**: 3–4 weeks for `exec` + `cp`, +1 week for `console`.

---

### P1 — Stats collection and alerting subsystem

**Why P1**: clustr currently exports Prometheus `/metrics` (server-side only)
but cannot answer "which nodes have a degraded RAID array right now?" without
external tooling. clustervisor's `cv-stats` + `cv-alerts` + the YAML rules is
a complete, self-contained, no-Prometheus-required answer that is part of the
operator's mental model. clustr doesn't need to clone the architecture, but it
does need to answer the same questions.

**Concrete shape (two viable paths)**:

#### Path A — Node-exporter style (recommended)

- Ship `clustr-statsd` (or fold it into `clustr-clientd`) — a node-side
  collector with the same plugin set clustervisor has:
  cpu, memory, disks (per-disk), MD/megaraid (RAID degraded), infiniband
  (link state, port counters), intelssd (NVMe wearout), nvidia (GPU temp,
  ECC, util), rocm (AMD GPU), ipmi (DCMI / SDR cache), nfs (mounts /
  exports), ntp (drift), tuned (active profile), zfs (pool state), firmware
  (BIOS / BMC / NIC versions), system (loadavg, uptime).
- Push metrics over the existing clientd WebSocket. New server table:
  `node_stats(node_id, plugin, sensor, value, ts)`.
- Provide `/metrics` Prometheus exposition that includes per-node series
  (replaces the current server-only metrics). Operators can already wire
  Grafana from there.
- Add `clustr stats -n NODE -s REGEX` CLI for ad-hoc queries.

#### Path B — Out-of-band only

- Reuse the cv-statsd OOB pattern: poll BMC (`external-bmc.py` equivalent)
  + SNMP (PDU, UPS, switch) from the server side without requiring an agent
  on the device. Useful for non-Linux hardware (PDUs, UPS, switches).

Both paths complement each other; ship Path A first because it covers the
common HPC compute-node case.

**Alerting**:

- Define alerting rules as YAML in `/etc/clustr/rules.d/*.yml`. Mirror
  clustervisor's set as the baseline so operators can copy rules across:
  `disk-percent`, `infiniband-down`, `hw-raid-degraded`, `sw-raid-degraded`,
  `zpool-degraded`, `cluster-mces-errors`, `cluster-nodes-offline`,
  `cluster-version` (mismatched clustr versions), `appliance-diskspacelow`.
- A new `internal/alerts/` package evaluates rules on a schedule (60s default)
  and emits to: the audit log, the SMTP notifier (already exists), the
  webhook dispatcher (already exists), and a new `/api/v1/alerts` endpoint.
- New CLI: `clustr alerts -L | -S | -R` and `clustr health [-s|-p|-w]` to
  match cv-alerts and cv-health.

**Time estimate**: 6–8 weeks for the agent + 5–6 plugins + a basic alerting
engine + UI surfacing on the Nodes page. Plugin parity with clustervisor's
full set is another 4–6 weeks of follow-up.

